of the forearm adjacent to the brachioradialis. Notice that their tendons cross the posterior (extensor) aspect of the wrist (carpi) on its lateral side (radialis). These muscles are the extensor carpi radialis longus and the extensor carpi radialis brevis.
Observe that the next muscle has four tendons that cross the posterior (extensor) aspect of the fingers (digitorum). The tendons of the extensor digitorum insert into the extensor expansions, CT structures that anchor the tendons to the bases of the distal two phalanges.  Extensor digitorum, therefore, is an extensor of the MCP, PIP and DIP joints. You might notice a small accessory extensor muscle that is dedicated to the fifth finger, the extensor digiti minimi.
Identify the final and most medial muscle in this layer, the extensor carpi ulnaris (ECU). Follow its tendon across the posterior aspect of the wrist on its medial side.
